===Order of battle===
UNCRO was commanded from UN Peace Force Headquarters (UNPF-HQ) established in [[Zagreb]]. UNPF-HQ controlled UNCRO, the [[United Nations Preventive Deployment Force]] (UNPREDEP) in the Republic of Macedonia, and UNPROFOR{{mdash}}which was confined to Bosnia and Herzegovina from late March.<ref name=Ahrens168>{{harvnb|Ahrens|2007|p=168}}</ref> The UNPF-HQ commander was French Lieutenant General [[Bernard Janvier]].<ref>{{harvnb|UNSC|18 April 1995|p=1}}</ref> In July, South Korean diplomat Byung Suk Min was appointed as head of UNCRO,<ref>{{harvnb|AP|3 July 1995}}</ref> with Major General Eid Kamal Al-Rodan of the [[Royal Jordanian Army]] as the mission's military commander.<ref>{{harvnb|UNSC|23 November 1995|p=1}}</ref> Before Al-Rodan, the post was held by Canadian Lieutenant General [[Raymond Crabbe]].<ref name=Ramet455>{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|pp=455–456}}</ref> UNCRO was initially deployed to the same parts of Croatia as UNPROFOR, however contemporary UNSC documents no longer referred to them as UNPAs—applying the designations of Sector East, West, North, and South, or "areas under the control of the local Serb authorities" instead.<ref name=UNSC981/><ref name=UNSC994>{{harvnb|UNSC|17 May 1995}}</ref><ref name=UNSC1025>{{harvnb|UNSC|30 November 1995}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|UNSC|1 May 1995}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|UNSC|4 May 1995}}</ref> One group of sources refers to the areas of UNCRO deployment as UNPAs,<ref>{{harvnb|Daniel|Hayes|1999|p=51}}</ref> another reflects the UNSC practice and omits the acronym,<ref>{{harvnb|Ramet|2006|p=456}}</ref> while others refer to the areas as "former UNPAs".<ref name=Ahrens168/>

Troops from Argentina, Belgium, Canada, Czech Republic, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Indonesia, Jordan, Kenya, Nepal, Netherlands, Norway, Poland, Russia, Slovakia, Sweden, Ukraine, and the United States contributed to the mission. When UNCRO replaced UNPROFOR in Croatia in March 1995, there were 15,229 UN troops{{mdash}}including UNPF-HQ personnel{{mdash}}in Croatia. By mid-November, the mission had been scaled down to 7,041 personnel, including 164 [[United Nations Military Observer|UN Military Observers]] and 296 [[UN Police|UN Civilian Police]] (UNCIVPOL) personnel.<ref name=UNSC23Nov95>{{harvnb|UNSC|23 November 1995|pp=13–14}}</ref><ref name=GAO1995>{{harvnb|GAO|1995|loc=Appendix II}}</ref>

